50|$|The Windows wait cursor (known as the <b>hourglass</b> <b>cursor</b> until Windows Vista) is a cursor that {{indicates}} that an application is busy performing an operation. It can be accompanied by an arrow if the operation is being performed in the background.|$|E
5000|$|Windows Vista {{introduced}} a new, animated wait cursor. The wait cursor in Windows 7 was almost identical. It is possible, however, {{to change the}} appearance of the cursor into the original <b>hourglass</b> <b>cursor.</b> On October 31, 2013, AppleInsider claimed that the macOS's counterpart, a [...] "beach ball cursor", was more recognized than Windows Vista's wait cursor due to the cultural impact that occurred after it appeared on a popular magazine.|$|E

